# This defines valid Plasm syntax for this prompt; reply with one valid plasm_program:
#
# Output choice:
# - Use a single `plasm_expr` only for one direct lookup/read/search/relation/method/action whose result is already the answer.
# - For **compositional** work (multiple steps, joins, reporting, summarization, writes, or any structured payload like markdown/html), use a **multi-line `plasm_program`** by defaultâ€”do not chain many one-line `plasm` calls.
# - Prefer a multi-line `plasm_program` for imperative/analytical/reporting goals: bind inputs, project only needed fields, limit/page intentionally, aggregate/group/sort, then return a small synthesized result.
#
# Syntax contract (pseudo-EBNF; TSV rows bind the catalogue-specific `plasm_expr` atoms):
# plasm_program ::= plasm_roots | binding+ plasm_roots
# binding       ::= ident "=" plasm_node
# plasm_roots   ::= plasm_return ("," plasm_return)*
# plasm_return  ::= node_ref | plasm_expr
# plasm_node    ::= plasm_expr | node_ref dag_suffix | node_ref "=>" plasm_value
# plasm_expr    ::= entity_expr [projection]
# entity_expr   ::= query_all | get | query | relation | method | create_action | search
# query_all     ::= e#
# get           ::= e#(id) or e#(p#=v, p#=v)
# query         ::= e#{p#=v, â€¦}
# relation      ::= e#(id).p#
# method        ::= e#(id).m#() or e#(id).m#(p#=v,..)
# create_action ::= e#.m#(args)
# projection    ::= e#(id)[p#,â€¦] | "[" fields "]"
# dag_suffix    ::= transform | "[" fields "]" | "[" fields "]" heredoc
# transform     ::= ".limit(" int ")" | ".sort(" field [", desc"] ")" | ".aggregate(" agg_spec ")" | ".group_by(" field "," agg_spec ")" | ".singleton()" | ".page_size(" int ")"
# fields        ::= [p#,â€¦]
# plasm_value   ::= literal | node_ref.field | _.field | [v, â€¦]
# ident/node_ref/field ::= agent-chosen names for bound nodes and fields
# literal      ::= quoted string | number | bool | null | heredoc
#
# Node-ref continuation:
# - When `ident` is bound to a **surface Plasm** row (get/query/relation result), writing `ident.<relation>` on the RHS continues that rowâ€™s expressionâ€”the compiler substitutes the bound anchor text and records a dependency on `ident`. Semantics match **repeating the full taught `plasm_expr` for that binding** and appending `.<relation>`. Synthetic steps (`ident[field,â€¦]`, `.limit`, `.aggregate`, `.group_by`, derive/`=>`, etc.) are **not** anchors and cannot be extended with `ident.<relation>`â€”repeat the full expression from DOMAIN instead.
#
# Program construction discipline:
# - **MCP `program` newline contract (read first):** For **compositional** workâ€”anything that is **not** a single taught `plasm_expr` on one physical lineâ€”you MUST put **literal newline characters (U+000A)** in the JSON `program` string between physical lines: **one line per `ident = â€¦` binding**, then final bare roots on their own line(s). **Spaces do not separate statements.** If you would write two bindings side-by-side with only spaces, that shape is **always wrong**; split with `
# ` before calling `plasm` / `plasm_run`. (Single-expression calls and single-line heredocs already satisfy this; multi-binding programs are where agents most often flatten incorrectly.)
# - Plan before executing: choose the final answer shape first, then bind only the necessary intermediate nodes.
# - Prefer `node[field,â€¦]`, `.limit(n)`, `.sort(...)`, `.aggregate(...)`, `.group_by(...)`, `.singleton()`, `.page_size(n)`, and render heredocs over returning raw broad lists.
# - Return at most small final roots unless the user explicitly asks for raw rows.
# - Use `page(sN_pgM)` only to continue a previously chosen list, not as exploratory browsing.
# - Do not perform probe calls whose only purpose is to inspect shape; the DOMAIN table is the contract.
# - MCP tool `plasm`: the JSON `program` field is one string that may include literal newlines (U+000A). For a `plasm_program`, write one physical line per `ident = â€¦` binding and final bare roots on their own line(s)â€”**never** one space-concatenated line for multiple bindings. A **tagged heredoc** is still **one logical statement**: after `<<TAG` you must have a newline immediately after `TAG` on the opener line, then the body lines, then a closing line whose trimmed text is `TAG` (or `TAG)` / `TAG,` / `TAG}` on that line). That spans multiple physical linesâ€”**do not** squash `<<TAG` onto the same line as the body.
# - **Final roots** may be comma-separated on one line **or** split across lines; commas **inside** a heredoc body never separate roots. Example: `e1.m2(p3=<<B
# Hello
# B
# ), e2` (comma after the heredoc closes on its `B` line, then the next root).
#
# Catalogue rules:
# - TSV `plasm_expr` cells teach executable catalogue atoms; `Meaning` explains how to choose and fill them.
# - Final program roots are **bare** comma-separated `plasm_expr` / `node_ref` lines (e.g. `e1, e2{...}`); do **not** prefix with `return` â€” that word is not Plasm syntax.
# - Never paste `Meaning`. Compose taught atoms with bindings/final roots only when a program is needed.
# - All semantic symbols you use must be taught in this prompt.
# - Projection uses a minimal non-empty subset from `[p#,â€¦]`; the identity row teaches the full set once.
# - Leading `p#` rows are metadata for slots when `args:` on a method line is not enough.
#
#   - e#, m#, p# are session-local aliases. Use the aliases **exactly** as shown in expression cells.
# - Pick rows by `Meaning`, then copy the `plasm_expr` shape. Bind args by keyed slot (`p12=value`), never by position or by renumbering.
# - Aliases are session-local. If a new prompt teaches new aliases, discard older e#/m#/p# meanings.
#   - e#(id) or e#(p#=v, p#=v) â€” get one entity by id or compound key (examples below use `v=$`, not concrete API values).
#   - Use TSV `plasm_expr` shapes exactly, substituting concrete values for placeholders.
#   - For compound-key forms such as `e#(id) or e#(p#=v, p#=v)`, keep keyed args (`p#=v` / `name=value`); never rewrite them as positional.
#   - e#{p#=v, â€¦} â€” list query; `e#` alone queries all.
#   - e#(id).p# â€” relation. e#(id).m#() or e#(id).m#(p#=v,..) â€” method call.
#   - For list/query goals, use brace predicates `e#{p#=v, â€¦}`. Use dotted `e#(id).m#() or e#(id).m#(p#=v,..)` only when the goal asks to mutate or call a method.
#   - e#.m#(args) â€” standalone create/action (no anchor id needed).
#   - e#(id)[p#,â€¦] â€” non-empty scalar subset. Dot after `e#(id)` means relations or taught `m#`, not scalar fields.
#   - To list X scoped by parent Y, use `X{p#=AnchorEntity(id)}` from X's rows; do not invent `Y(id).p#`.
#   - `[v, â€¦]` â€” array value inside method args, e.g. `p#=[e#($)]`.
#   - Plain `str` values use double quotes. In quoted strings only `\"` and `\\` are escapes.
#   - `select` chooses one listed allowed value; `multiselect` chooses zero or more as `[v, â€¦]`.
#   - When `Meaning` marks a slot used in an input value as `markdown`, `html`, `document`, `json_text`, or `blob`, use tagged heredoc only: `<<TAG` ... `TAG`.
# - Example: `m#(..., p#=<<TXT` newline body newline `TXT` newline `)`.
#   - e#~"text" â€” full-text search on entities whose teaching rows include a `~` example (same entities only).
#   - `p#`-only rows predeclare slots; they are metadata, not expressions to output.
#   - `$` is only a fill-in cue. Substitute a real value; never send `$`.
# - `..` â€” optional params may follow (`optional params:` lists them, comma-separated). `..` can appear alone when all args are optional.
#   - TSV rows are teaching rows. `plasm_expr` teaches syntax; `Meaning` teaches selection and argument semantics.
#

